@brief
Get the mask for a given object in a given source image. The mask intrinsic position and size is given by 
the rect returned by ctstrobe_getObjectRect upscaled with the size from ctstrobe_getMapsDimensions.
The mask will be stretched from its intrinsic size to fill the provided bitmap. 

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param sourceIndex
Index of relevant source. 

@param objectIndex
Index of relevant object.

@param objectColor
Color of mask foreground. Mask background is black, and transparent if the color format supports transparency.  

@param[out] pOutBitmap
Output bitmap. If the dimensions are not the same as the size of the object rect (as retrievable by getObjectRect) it will be stretched.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Get a bounding rect around object

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param sourceIndex
Index of relevant source. 

@param objectIndex
Index of relevant object.

@param[out] pObjectRect
Bounding rect for this object. Dimensions from 0.0f to 1.0f, relative to the map dimensions.

@sa ctstrobe_getMapDimensions().

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Get number of objects detected in a given source image.

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param sourceIndex
Index of relevant source. 

@return Number of detected objects upon success. 0 upon failure.

@brief
Get number of objects detected in a given source image.

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param sourceIndex
Index of relevant source. 

@param[out] pCount
Number of detected objects.

@return CERR_OK on success.

    @brief
    Sets the amount of blur to be used when the motionblur effect is applied.
	The length of the motion blur is proportional to the image size and the speed.
	With speed set to 1.0 the blur length is about 1/14th of the image width.

    @param pStrobe
    Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

    @param speed
    The intensity of the motionblur. Must to be >= 0.0 and recommended range is [0.0, 1.0].

    @return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Set if shadow detection should be use when rendering. This should put shadows behind regular objects.

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param shadowDetection
If true shadow detection will be used when blending, otherwise false.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief Set features to activate when using the CTSTROBE_MOTION_BLUR_PATHS choice with ctstrobe_setBackgroundEffect().
@param pStrobe Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.
@param pathEffect Bitfield of desired effect(s). Several effects can be added at the same time.
@param pSourceImagesInPath Vector of CTBool indicating which source images (and associated objects) should be used to build the path. The size of the vector should be the same as returned by ctstrobe_getNumberOfSources(). This parameter can be set to 0/NULL, in this case the previous source image selection vector will be used. Default vector is using all input images. Example: Vector {TRUE, FALSE, FALSE..., FALSE, TRUE} would include only the objects found in first and last source image.
@param pClipArtBitmap Bitmap to randomly fill the path area if CTSTROBE_FILLPATH_ADDCLIPART bit is enabled. Must be CM_YUV420P. The bitmaps will be placed randomly inside the moving object path. The position for clip-art top-left coordinate is randomized within the moving path mask, thus parts of the clip-art image might be placed outside the mask if the top-left random coordinate happens to be placed on the edge of the mask. The clipart bitmaps will be blended onto the cleaned background, then the "moving objects" will be blended on top of the clipart bitmaps. The client is responsible for maintaing the memory for the bitmap and release it when the Strobe instance is no longer needed.
@param pClipArtMask Alpha mask to use when blending in the pClipArtBitmap if CTSTROBE_FILLPATH_ADDCLIPART bit is set. Must be CM_GRAY8 and same size as pClipArtBitmap. The client is responsible for maintaing the memory for the bitmap and release it when the Strobe instance is no longer needed.
@param numClipArtCopies Number of times the clip art bitmap is copied on top of the target bitmap.
@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Set the effect to use on the background image. Must be called before rendering.

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param backgroundEffect
Desired effect.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Set the blending method to use when rendering.

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param blendMethod
Desired blend method to use when rendering.

@return CERR_OK on success.

Utility function that checks if there exists >= 2 input images with >= 1 objects detected each.
This is the only criteria checked and the result might differ from the ctstrobe_getOptimalSourceSelection
which does more detailed analysis with overlapping criteria. This function is to be used to check if 
there is enough input to do strobe at all.

@param[in] pStrobe Strobe instance. Analyze must have been called prior to this function
@param[out] pIsPossible. True or false according to criteria.

@return CERR_OK on success.

Get the size of the internal object maps in the strobe object.
@param pStrobe Strobe instance.
@return The size of the internal object maps.

Get an overdraw image where the pixel value is set to the number of objects that cover the pixel.

@param[in] pStrobe Strobe instance. ctstrobe_analyze() must have been called prior to this function.
@param[out] pCount Counting bitmap. Must be CM_GRAY8. Must have the size given by ctstrobe_getMapDimensions().
@param[in] pUseSource Optional. Array of size number of images in strobe. Set each element to true or false in order to get the overdraw count
if not images are used. 0 assumes all images are used.

@return CERR_OK on success.

Find out which images should be used for optimal resulting strobe, and if strobe is at all possible.
Strobe is possible if object cover meets the input criteria and if there is >= 2 input images with >= 1 objects detected each.

Terms used:
Cover: number_of_pixels_with_>=1_objects / all_pixels
Overdraw: number_of_pixels_with_>=2_objects / number_of_pixels_with_>=1_objects

@param[in] pStrobe Strobe instance.
@param[in] mainImage Index of the source to use as the baseline of the render operation
@param[out] pUseSource Array of size == number of strobe sources. Output is set to true if source should be part of output.
@param[out] pStrobePossible True if strobe is at all possible for this series.
@param[in] minCover Minimum cover. Recommended: 0.03f
@param[in] maxCover Maximum cover. Recommended: 0.5f
@param[in] maxOverdraw Maximum overdraw. Recommended: 0.5f

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Perform render of the result image

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@param pImages
Valid CTBitmap array containing aligned images of the same size. The number of images must match the amount images used for analyze.
Colormode must be CM_YUV420P and the size must correspond to a 2-exponent scale of ctremove_getMapsSize() (from 1 to 32).

@param sourceIndex
Index of the source to use as the baseline of the render operation.

@param pOutBitmap
The target bitmap. Must be CM_YUV420P and same dimensions as pImages.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Perform analysis of the images, moving objects will be identified.
This method may take a while. 

@param pImages
Valid CTBitmap array containing aligned images of the same size. Must be YUV420P.

@param numSources Number of images

@param[out] ppStrobe Created CTStrobeObjects instance.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@remark Internally the images will be downscaled to a suitable size for analysis, to get
the internal size, use ctstrobe_getMapDimensions().

@remark The CTStrobeObjects instance will be created with the following deafult settings:
Blend method: CTSTROBE_MEAN_BLEND
Background effect: CTSTROBE_STANDARD_BACKGROUND
Shadow detection: false
Blur speed: 0.5

@brief Gets the number of added sources to the given Strobe instance.

@param pStrobe Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@return The number of added sources. If an invalid instance is used zero will be returned.

@brief
Destroys a CTStrobeObjects object.

@param pStrobe
Valid CTStrobeObjects instance.

@brief Strobes moving objects by combining a series of images.
Strobe analyzes a series of images to separate moving objects from background. Objects can then be extracted from the source images and inserted into one image, producing a strobe.
Usage -# Align images using any method, for example CTAligner. -# Analyze images using ctstrobe_analyze. This operation may take some time. -# Optional: Manage detected objects' visibility and visualize detected objects by using the object related functions. -# Render result using ctstrobe_render(). -# Destroy the CTStrobeObjects object, ctstrobe_destroy() .

@brief
Create a stream from a buffer.

This function will create a stream object that uses a @c CTBuffer as 
underlying resource. 

For output streams, the buffer can grow to a max size expecified as a 
parameter, which means that the internal pointer in the @c CTBuffer 
object ( @c data member ), can be freed and allocated internally multiple 
times.

@param pBuffer The input buffer that will be used to read or write data to.
The CTBuffer struct that pBuffer points to must be valid during the whole
life time of the CTStream.
@param maxBuffer max size the buffer can become when writing data to it. 
Zero means that it can grow as much as needed. Initial buffer size is fetched
from the input buffer.
@param pExtraContext Extra context sent to the buffer. This context will
be sent as an argument to destroyFunc. If set to null, a null parameter
is passed to destroyFunc (if one is provided).
@param destroyFunc Extra destroy function called when the buffer stream
is destroyed. pExtraContext is sent as an argument to this function. The
function is called after all other destruction has been processed. If set
to null, the function will not be called.

@param[out] ppStream Pointer to an stream object.

When the stream object (returned by this function) is no longer needed, it
should be destroyed using: ctstream_destroy()

@return
@li @c CERR_OK if successful or a specific error code upon failure.

@note The extra context can be used to, for instance, automatically destroy
a buffer when the stream is destroyed.

@since 3.8

@ingroup scb_ctstream_buffer
@file ctstream_buffer.h
@brief Buffer based stream creation.

@addtogroup scb_ctstream_buffer
@brief Creation of buffer streams
@{

    @brief
    Create a stream from a buffer.

    This function will create a stream object that uses a @c CTBuffer as 
    underlying resource. 

    For output streams, the buffer can grow to a max size expecified as a 
    parameter, which means that the internal pointer in the @c CTBuffer 
    object ( @c data member ), can be freed and allocated internally multiple 
    times.

    @param pBuffer The input buffer that will be used to read or write data to.
    The CTBuffer struct that pBuffer points to must be valid during the whole
    life time of the CTStream.
    @param maxBuffer max size the buffer can become when writing data to it. 
    Zero means that it can grow as much as needed. Initial buffer size is fetched
    from the input buffer.

    @param[out] ppStream Pointer to an stream object.

    When the stream object (returned by this function) is no longer needed, it
    should be destroyed using: ctstream_destroy()

    @return
    @li @c CERR_OK if successful or a specific error code upon failure.

    @since 3.8

@brief
Performs segmentation of the image that the segmenter was created with 
based on the grab cut approach.

Use @ctsegmenter_prepare() to speed to up the first call.

@param pSegmenter
Segmenter object.

@param pSelect
A bitmap (CM_BGRA8888) scribbled to indicates foreground and background in the 
image that the segmenter was created with.
() @cscribbleFGValue indicates foreground pixels.
() @cscribbleBGValue indicates background pixels.
() @selectedValue    indicates the selected area in the grabcut sense.
() Black indicates unclassified pixels.
The dimensions of the bitmap must be the same as "previewDims" that the segmenter
was created with.

@param[in,out] pMask
The mask (CM_GRAY8) resulting from the segmentation, foreground pixels are white 
and background pixels are black.
The dimensions of the bitmap must be the same as "previewDims" that the segmenter
was created with.

@param selectedValue The pixel value that should be considered as selected area.

@param selectedValue Max number of grab cut iterations.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Fill the cooresponding superpixels marked in mask

@param pSegmenter
Segmenter object.

@param[in,out] pMask
The mask (CM_GRAY8) resulting from the segmentation, foreground pixels are white 
and background pixels are black.
The dimensions of the bitmap must be the same as the image that the segmenter 
was created with.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief
Gets the resulting mask in full resolution (size that corresponds to the 
image that the segmenter was created with).
This operation may only be called after a succesful @c ctsegmenter_segment.

@param pSegmenter
Segmenter object.

@param[in,out] pMask
The mask (CM_GRAY8) resulting from the segmentation, foreground pixels are white 
and background pixels are black.
The dimensions of the bitmap must be the same as the image that the segmenter 
was created with.

@return CERR_OK on success.

@brief Performs segmentation of the image that the segmenter was created with based on scribbles on foreground and background pixels. This operation may be called several times.
Use @ctsegmenter_prepare() to speed to up the first call. Use @ctsegmenter_getResultMask() inorder to retrieve the full resolution mask after the final segmentation.
@param pSegmenter Segmenter object.
@param pScribble A bitmap (CM_BGRA8888) scribbled to indicates foreground and background in the image that the segmenter was created with. () @cscribbleFGValue indicates foreground pixels. () @cscribbleBGValue indicates background pixels. () Black indicates unclassified pixels. The dimensions of the bitmap must be the same as "previewDims" that the segmenter was created with.
@param[in,out] pMask The mask (CM_GRAY8) resulting from the segmentation, foreground pixels are white and background pixels are black. The dimensions of the bitmap must be the same as "previewDims" that the segmenter was created with.
@return CERR_OK on success.

